millions of listeners around the world and contributed to radio’s success as a mass media form in the 1930s and 1940s. But Corwin was also a pioneer in other fields, including cinema, theater, TV, and journalism. In each of these areas, he had a distinctive approach to “soundwork,” relying on inventive prerecorded and live-in-real-time atmospheric effects in the studio, among other aesthetic techniques. Exploring the range of Corwin’s work—from his World War II–era poetry and his special projects for the United Nations to his path-breaking writing for film and television—and its influence on media today, these essays underscore the political and social impact of Corwin’s oeuvre and cement his reputation as a key writer in the history of many sound media.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aRadio broadcastingzUnited States. 0aRadio producers and directorszUnited States. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Media Studies.2bisacsh1 aBerard, Jeanette, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrown, Ross, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCrook, Tim, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCummings, Troy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDoherty, Thomas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHilmes, Michele, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOssman, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRusso, Alexander, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSmith, Jacob, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSmith, Jacob, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aVancour, Shawn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aVerma, N